The course serves as an introduction to the most important anatomical, physiological, ecological and evolutionary characteristics of invertebrates. The course covers the phylogenetics of major invertebrate phyla and introduces major species and their distribution in the world.

The practical course introduces basic morphology and anatomy of major groups of  invertebrates by examining some more widespread/ important species from each major phylum. Conserved samples, dry preparations, micropreparations, and the collections of Zoology Museum are at students disposal.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to give an overview of invertebrates species by major taxa. The aim of the practical works is exploration of morphology and anatomy of the representitives of the major invertebrate groupsLearning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After passing the course, the student: 1. Has achieved a level that enables to continue independent studies in zoology 2. Has a basic overview about essential aspects of invertebrate morphology, physiology, ecology and systematics of invertebrates 3. Is able to discuss the topics related to importance, anatomy, physiology, evolution and distribution of invertebrates.
